  "summary": "Following the Carpenters' dinner, Mrs. Oliver approaches Hercule Poirot on the terrace to speak privately. She provides him with a note identifying Dr. Lundell as the murderer, claiming his motive was that Miss Macquart discovered he was practicing medicine illegally. Poirot expresses skepticism regarding her certainty. He informs Mrs. Oliver that someone attempted to push him onto the tracks at Gilchester station the previous night at 9:35. While Mrs. Oliver notes that Dr. Lundell made a house call during that time, Poirot observes that several people's whereabouts remain unverified, noting that the maid, Frieda, was at the movies and could not provide alibis for those at Hunter's Manor. Mrs. Oliver provides an alibi for Robin Upward and his mother, stating they were playing cards with her from 8:00 to 10:30.\n\nPoirot complains about the poor food and conditions at Mrs. Samuels' residence. During the conversation, Muriel Samuels joins them appearing intoxicated from gin. She becomes emotional while discussing her own adoption, expressing her belief that mothers should never abandon their children. After the guests depart, the group visits Mrs. Upward at the Golden Chain Garden. A discussion arises regarding genetics versus environment. Mrs. Upward asserts that bloodline and genetics are the most important factors in determining character, a sentiment supported by Johnny Sams. This leads Mrs. Oliver to question the extent of hereditary traits across generations.",
